{{About|knowledge in Buddhism and Dzogchen|the organization|Rigpa organization}}
{{more footnotes|date=June 2014}}
[[File:Dzogchen A.png|thumb|Tibetan letter "A" inside a thigle. The A, which corresponds to the sound ‘ahh’,{{sfn|Norbu|2002|p=56}} represents kadag while the thigle represents lhun grub.]]
{{Tibetan Buddhism}}
In [[Dzogchen]] teaching, '''rigpa''' ({{bo|t=རིག་པ་|w=rig pa}}; Skt. [[Vidya (Knowledge)|vidyā]]; "knowledge") is the knowledge of the [[Ground (Dzogchen)|ground]].{{refn|group=note|''ghzi''; Skrt. ''ālaya''{{sfn|Schaik|2004|p=5}}}} The opposite of rigpa is marigpa ([[Avidyā (Buddhism)|avidyā]], ignorance).

==Definition==
''Rigpa'' is the knowledge of the [[Ground (Dzogchen)|ground]].{{refn|group=note|''ghzi''; Skrt. ''ālaya''{{sfn|Schaik|2004|p=5}}}} [[Erik Pema Kunsang]] translates a text which provides basic definitions of rigpa and marigpa in a Dzogchen context:
{{quote|Unknowing (marigpa) is not knowing the nature of mind. Knowing (rigpa) is the knowing of the original wakefulness that is personal experience.{{sfn|Kunsang|2006|p=Chapter 15}}}}
In Dzogchen, a fundamental point of practice is to distinguish rigpa from sems (''[[citta]]'', (grasping) mind).{{sfn|Kunsang|2012|p=154}}

===Kadag and lhungrub===
Rigpa has two aspects, namely ''kadag'' and ''lhun grub''.{{sfn|Dalai Lama|2004|p=32}} ''Kadag'' means "purity" or specifically "primordial purity".{{sfn|Rinpoche Dzogchen Ponlop|2003}}{{sfn|Dalai Lama|2004|p=30}} ''Lhun grub'' in Tibetan normally implies automatic, self-caused or spontaneous actions or processes.{{sfn|Hookham|1991|p=49-50}} As quality of ''rigpa'' it means "spontaneous presence"{{sfn|Rinpoche Dzogchen Ponlop|2003}}{{refn|group=note|name="lhun grub"|See also [http://rywiki.tsadra.org/index.php/lhun_grub rywiki, ''lhun grub'']}} It may also mean "having a self-contained origin", being primordially Existent, without an origin, self-existent.{{sfn|Hookham|1991|p=49-50}} This division is the Dzogchen-equivalent of the more common Mahayana wisdom and compassion division.{{sfn|Dalai Lama|2004|p=32}}

===Full measure of rigpa===
Citing Dodrupchen Jikme Tenpe Nyima, the 14th Dalai Lama states the full measure of rigpa occurs with the [http://www.rigpawiki.org/index.php?title=Four_visions third vision].{{sfn|Dalai Lama|2004|p=183-4}}

==Practice==
{{See also|Dzogchen#Main practice}}

Dzogchen practices aim to attain rigpa and integrate this into everyday life:
{{quote|The practical training of the Dzogchen path is traditionally, and most simply, described in terms of View, Meditation and Action. To see directly the Absolute state, the Ground of our being is the View; the way of stabilising that view, and making it an unbroken experience is Meditation; and integrating the View into our entire reality, and life, is what is meant by Action.<ref>Sogyal Rinpoche (1992), ''The Tibetan Book of Living and Dying'', p.151]</ref>}}

The [[Menngagde]] or 'Instruction Class' of Dzogchen teachings are divided into two parts: ''Trekchö'' and ''Tögal'' (thod rgal). Ron Garry: 
{{quote|The practice is that of Cutting through Solidity (khregs chod), which is related to primordial purity (ka dag); and Direct Vision of Reality (thod rgal), which is related to spontaneous presence (Ihun grub).<ref name="Dudjom Rinpoche 2005, page 296">Dudjom Rinpoche. ''Wisdom Nectar. '' Snow Lion 2005, page 296.</ref>}}

